Introduction

In the context of mixed models, we are discussing the importance on using different var-cov structures to model GxE interaction. However, when a large number of environments is presented, the number of parameters to be estimated grows quadratically with the number of trials so it quickly becomes too many parameters to estimate. For this reason, it is common to recall to var-cov matrices that are symmetric, so less parameters can be estimated. Among the main methods, Factor Analytic Model has its moment in the GxE literature given the high flexibility and meaningful results.

Theory

Factor Analytic (FA) Model

FA var-cov structures offer a more parsimonious approach to describe covariance among environments. As an example in trials with 5,10 and 50 environments we need to estimate 15, 55 and 1275 parameters using an unstructure form. On the other hand, FA models are used as parsimonious approximations to unstructured models and we need to estimate 10, 20 and 100 parameters to fit the same model.

Important advantages on using FA models:

  • Ability to adequately capture the often complex variance structure without the use of an excessive number of variance parameters.
  • In the case of a less than full rank variance structure for the G Ã E effects can be accommodated, provided that an appropriate estimation algorithm is implemented.

First important point when fitting a FA model is to realize that genetic and environment factors can be written as a latent variable arising from a multiplicative (or regression) model. Therefore, in a linear model, we need to replace our genetic term by a multiplicative additive genetic effect for individual i and environment j. We can write it as:

\[u_{a_{ij}} = \lambda_{a1} f_{a1i}+\lambda_{a2} f_{a2i}+...+\lambda_{akj} f_{aki} + \delta_{aij}\]

\[u_{ge_{ij}} = \sum^k_{l=1} \lambda_{jl}f_{il} + \delta_{ij}\]

Where

  • \(\lambda_{jl}\) is the loading for environment represented as a l-th environmental covariate at the j-th environment and is called as the
  • \(f_{il}\) is the slope or the score for i-th genotype for the l-th environment covariate
  • \(\delta\) is the residual GxE.

Some important point:

  • It is like a linear regression model except the covariates are estimated from the data.
  • Loading represent some latent environmental covariate.

In a vector notation, we can write the same information as:

\[u_a = (I_m \otimes \Lambda_a)f_a + \delta_a\]

where \(\Lambda\) is the txk matrix of environment loading, \(f_a\) is the mkx1 vector of additive genetic scores and \(\sigma_a\) is the mtx1 vector of genetic regression residuals.

We can make some important extensions of this base model and present the genetic effects in terms of breeding values by additing a relationship matrix in its formulation. For example, we can assume that both \(f_a\) and \(\sigma_a\) are independent and are distributed as multivariate Gaussian with zero means and variance matrices given by:

\[var(f_a) = A \otimes I_k\]

\[var(\delta_a)= A \otimes \Psi_a\]

where \(\Psi_a\) is a \(t \times t\) diagonal matrix diagonal matrix with a variance (known as a specific variance) for each environment. These assumptions lead to:

\[var(u_a) = G_a = A \otimes (\Lambda_a\Lambda^T_a + \Psi_a)\]

As many multivariate analyses a key process is to maximize the variance in few components. For example, this is the central ideal underlying typical PCA analyses.Here, we have the same issue and the number of \(k\) can change increasing the complexity of the models. How to define the best k? To determine an appropriate value of k , we use a measure similar to an R2 goodness-of-fit value for a multiple regression. This is partly driven by the fact that predicted breeding values for individual trials are based on the multiplicative terms alone, that is, the genetic regression residuals are excluded. In a matrix notation, we could use the following equation, in which we measure the percentage of additive genetic variance accounted for by the \(k\) multiplicative terms:

\[v_{a_j}= 100 \dfrac{tr \Lambda\Lambda^T}{tr (\Lambda\Lambda^T + \Psi)}\] We choose an order such that the overall percentage variance accounted for is high and the number of trials with low individual v a j values is small.

Hands on

Pinus data set

  • Download the pinus data set (Pine_polymix.csv).
    • Link for the example.
    • Description: goal is to predict breeding values of females and carry out family selection. 79 individuals were mated with bulked pollen collected from another set of 40 individuals. Progeny from crossing were considered half-sibs with known mother and different fathers. A randomized complete block design was used with 20 blocks at each of 10 sites. Each female parent had one progeny in each block, for a total of 20 progeny at a site at the time of the planting.
Effect Observation Levels
site location of the progeny test 12
block replication number 20
female GCA effect 70
height response variable numeric

# FA1
mm.FA1 = asreml(fixed = height ~ 1 + site , 
             random = ~ block:site + fa(site,1):female, 
             residual=~dsum(~id(units)|site),
             data = data)

As FA can be interpreted as a random regression, we can run some additional analyses and get the latent regression plots. To help on this task, we will use the agriutilities package and some functions that implemented there. The agriutilities webpage has more details. But here, we will focus on few tasks:

  • Create a heatmap to check the correlation between the environments
  • Regplots: stability and performance
  • Biplots
library(agriutilities)
library(lattice)

# Latent Plots
ASM <- fa.asreml(mm.FA2, 
                 regplot = T,
                 uniplot = T,
                 addedplot = T,
                 heatmap = T,
                 g.list = c("1", "117", "119", "122", "128"))
ASM$heatmaps$`fa(site, 2):female`

ASM$regplots$`fa(site, 2):female`

# Other summary
pp = predict(mm.FA2, classify = "site")$pvals
